---
// src/components/PaidQuerySnapshot.astro
//
// Tiny inline script that snapshots window.location.search into a global
// (window.__BHQ_INBOUND_QUERY__) the instant it parses. Mount this AS
// EARLY AS POSSIBLE on any page that needs to forward inbound Google Ads
// tracking parameters onto downstream signup links.
//
// Why this exists:
//   Google's gtag.js (loaded by the marketing site's Analytics.astro
//   component) is `<script async>`. Async scripts execute as soon as
//   they download, which on a modern network is faster than parsing
//   ~54KB of HTML to reach an inline script positioned mid-body. Inside
//   the GA4 config, gtag consumes `gclid` from the URL and rewrites the
//   address bar via history.replaceState — by design, to keep gclid out
//   of bookmarks and shared links. Any later script that reads
//   window.location.search to forward the gclid onto a signup link
//   loses the race and sees the stripped URL.
//
// The fix is to capture the gclid (and the entire query string) BEFORE
// gtag has a chance to load and run. This component renders a single
// inline `<script>` with no external dependencies — the browser
// executes it the instant the parser hits it. Mount it inside <head>
// or at the very top of <body>, BEFORE the Analytics.astro component
// renders its gtag tag.
//
// Downstream consumers (PaidTrafficHero.astro) read from
// window.__BHQ_INBOUND_QUERY__ instead of window.location.search.
//
// This is a one-shot snapshot: it does NOT track route changes (the
// marketing site is static-rendered, so route changes are full page
// loads anyway), and it does NOT modify the URL itself.
---

<script is:inline>
  // Snapshot the inbound URL query string as early as possible so we
  // can forward gclid + utm_* onto signup links even after gtag.js has
  // consumed and stripped gclid from window.location.search.
  window.__BHQ_INBOUND_QUERY__ = window.location.search || "";
</script>
